<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="228" pageId="3" pageNumber="227" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1812,2091]" box="[189,1012,1884,1911]" pageId="3" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,312,1884,1911]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="227">Etymology</emphasis>
:—Name derived from the plant host species 
<taxonomicName box="[820,1005,1884,1910]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Gomesa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="3" pageNumber="227" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="recurva">
<emphasis box="[820,1005,1884,1910]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="227">Gomesa recurva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,1812,2091]" pageId="3" pageNumber="227">
Colonies on PDA growing 
<quantity box="[503,585,1920,1947]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="51.0">51 mm</quantity>
in 3 d, flat with entire edges, dense aerial mycelium, white; reverse of the colony white to cream. Hyphae are regularly septate branching out at right angles, with 3.2–6.1 µm in diameter (± SD = 4.7 ± 0.59 µm), hyaline, with binucleated cells and thick walls. Monilioid cells hyaline, elongated in shape of a barrel, 10.1–12.7 µm de diam. (± SD = 11.1 ± 0.76 µm), branched chains with more than four cells. Sexual structure not observed.
</paragraph>
